				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$u_{i,t - p}$$\end{document}ui,t-p as additional source of newly reported COVID-19 cases adds a further predictive element to our SP-ECM approach, which complements the short-run parameter estimates.

The temporal distribution of the spatial adjustment component in Panel B of Fig. 4 supports our theoretical considerations that a spatial disequilibrating force (driven by emerging local hot spots) is observed if regions move along an exponential growth path of infections. Our estimation results indicate that this was particularly relevant in the initial phase of the first pandemic wave in Germany during calendar weeks 7 to 9. Hereafter, the effects turn nonsignificant pointing to a flatting of the German infection curve. With the imposition of mobility constraints, we further get evidence for an emerging equilibrating process as indicated by negative coefficients for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$u_{i,t - p}$$\end{document}ui,t-p. Together with the general trend results in Panel A, this indicates that the first wave of new COVID-19 cases peaked around calendar week 13 (starting on March 23, 2020).

